      "question": "If $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ are the roots of the quadratic equation $x^2 - 5x + 3 = 0$, find the value of $\\frac{1}{\\alpha} + \\frac{1}{\\beta} - \\alpha\\beta$.",
      "answer": "$\\frac{-14}{3}$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the sum and product of the roots using the relations $\\alpha + \\beta = -b/a$ and $\\alpha\\beta = c/a$.",
          "Express the required expression $\\frac{1}{\\alpha} + \\frac{1}{\\beta} - \\alpha\\beta$ as $\\frac{\\alpha + \\beta}{\\alpha\\beta} - \\alpha\\beta$.",
          "Substitute the values $\\alpha + \\beta = 5$ and $\\alpha\\beta = 3$ into the expression.",
          "Calculate the final result."
        ],
        "derivation": "For $x^2 - 5x + 3 = 0, \\text{ we have } a=1, b=-5, c=3. \\\\ \\alpha + \\beta = -(-5)/1 = 5 \\\\ \\alpha\\beta = 3/1 = 3 \\\\ \\frac{1}{\\alpha} + \\frac{1}{\\beta} - \\alpha\\beta = \\frac{\\alpha + \\beta}{\\alpha\\beta} - \\alpha\\beta \\\\ = \\frac{5}{3} - 3 \\\\ = \\frac{5 - 9}{3} = \\frac{-4}{3}"
      },
